      1) Introduction¶

      18
       
      1
      This notebook corresponds to the first part of the deliverable that will be handed-in to the company. It is comprised by two parts and their associated Key Performance Indicators:
      2
      * An assessment of credit card payments and how can Olist improve cashflow - the associated KPI is accounts receivable age;
      3
      * An assessment of customer's written reviews through NLP - the associated KPI is customer satisfaction (rating).
      4
      ​
      5
      For both analysis knowledge of the country and language are needed, both being natural to the athour, who was born and has lived in Brazil for more than 28 years. The motivation of working with these two KPIs (although no tool or method from the course will be used for the first one) comes from previous experiences that showed how much, in Brazil, simple rules regarding payments can improve a company's finances and its ability to have more positiev cashflow, and how much sometimes higher management is unaware of customer's pains.
      6
      ​
      7
      The datasets used for this report may be found [here](https://www.kaggle.com/olistbr/brazilian-ecommerce), and a brief explanation of them below:
      8
      * olist_order_reviews_dataset: data from the reviews provided by customers (rating and written);
      9
      * olist_orders_dataset: core dataset from orders;
      10
      * olist_customers_dataset: information about customers and their location;
      11
      * olist_geolocation_dataset: Brazilian zip codes and their coordinates;
      12
      * olist_order_payments_dataset: specifics from payment methods for the purchases.
      13
      ​
      14
      This part of the deliverable aims to make recommendations for Olist on how to apply the tools presented herein, or how to conduct further, more directed analysis.

      # <font color=blue>2)</font> Cashflow

      2) Cashflow¶

      1
       
      1
      ### <font color=blue>2.1)</font> Context

      2.1) Context¶

      11
       
      1
      The cashflow of a company is the movement of money through a certain period of time. In the present study, only monthly in-flow from revenues will be analyzed, specifically from credit card purchases in installments.
      2
      ​
      3
      Installments are not extremely known and practiced in many countries besides Brazil (although in recent years many third-parties have been offering _get now, pay-later_ options, like [Klarna](https://www.klarna.com/uk/business/products/instalments/)), but it is one of the most popular payment methods there. Basically, companies can sell goods to customers and offer them the option of payment all up-front (through cash, debit/credit card or "boleto") or to split their payment in installments (with or without interests) using their credit card. The customer's bank takes into account the total value of the purchase in order to control the customer's purchase limit, but the money is not withdrawn from his/her account, and the service/goods provider **does not** receive the money up-front. On the contrary, usually the first installment will be credited to the business after 30 days, and then each will follow with 30 days intervals as well.
      4
      ​
      5
      Sometimes the company puts a mark-up (interests) on that type of payment, but since there is no data available about interests, it is assumed that no interests are added.
      6
      ​
      7
      It is easy to understand that, if a company offers payments in 12 installments for all customers, its cashflow has been seriously impacted. Accounts receivable (how much a company expects to have of cash in-flow from already performed sales in a certain period of time) is a financial health related KPI that is used very frequently by companies as a warranty (when borrowing money from banks, for example). Added to that, Brazil is a country that has a somewhat unstable economy, and inflation is a reality - if someone owns 10 BRL to a company today, that money is not worth the same amount 12 months later.
      8
      ​
      9
      On the other hand, if customer do not have the option of splitting their payments on large purchases, the company might lose the sell, and that's generally worse than not selling.
      10
      ​
      11
      Therefore, companies usually create payment rules: up until a certain amount, clients can only pay up-front; from the first value threshold, clients can split up until 3 installments; and so forth, up until the last threshold, where any purchase with a value above it will be allowed to be split into that ceiling of installments (from 3 to 12 installments is very common for medium and large sized businesses).

      ### <font color=blue>2.5)</font> Recommendation

      2.5) Recommendation¶

      1
       
      1
      A new installments "rule book" can disrupt frequent clients' perception of fairness when it comes to payment. It is recommended that Olist performs beta versions of this new initiative, such as A/B testing or customer surveys, and perhaps not aim for the optimized values (which also do not make much sense, business wise), but rather for one that brings sufficient improvements and at the same time reduces customer's rejection (such as the first one suggested).

      A new installments "rule book" can disrupt frequent clients' perception of fairness when it comes to payment. It is recommended that Olist performs beta versions of this new initiative, such as A/B testing or customer surveys, and perhaps not aim for the optimized values (which also do not make much sense, business wise), but rather for one that brings sufficient improvements and at the same time reduces customer's rejection (such as the first one suggested).

      def text_processing(text):
      5
          # remove punctuation
      6
          text = ''.join([c for c in text
      7
                          if c not in string.punctuation])
      8
          # lowercase
      9
          text = ''.join([c.lower() for c in text])
      10
      11
          # remove stopwords
      12
          text = ' '.join([w for w in text.split()
      13
                           if w not in stopwords])
      14
          # remove empty tokens
      15
          text = ''.join([t for t in text if len(t) > 0])
      16
      17
          # stemming
      18
          text = ' '.join([stemmer.stem(c) for c in text.split()])
      19
      20
          # removing language specific characters
      21
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('á'): 'a'}) for s in text])
      22
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('é'): 'e'}) for s in text])
      23
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('í'): 'i'}) for s in text])
      24
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('ó'): 'o'}) for s in text])
      25
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('ú'): 'u'}) for s in text])
      26
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('à'): 'a'}) for s in text])
      27
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('ã'): 'a'}) for s in text])
      28
          text = ''.join([s.translate({ord('õ'): 'o'}) for s in text])
      29
      30
          return text

      def word_frequency(reviews):
      2
          word_freq = {}
      3
          word_count = 0
      4
          for review in reviews:
      5
              words = [word.strip(string.punctuation) for word in review.split()]
      6
              for word in words:
      7
                  if word not in word_freq:
      8
                      word_freq[word] = 0
      9
                  word_freq[word] += 1
      10
                  word_count += 1
      11
          for word in word_freq:
      12
              word_freq[word] /= word_count
      13
          return word_freq

      The plot above shows the amount of orders per month (for all the years of the dataset) on the top, and the percentage of those orders which, according to the present assessment, got a bad review due to delivery timing issues. A few things may be discussed:
      2
      * It is curious to see that, although the months of May-August are between the highest ones in terms of volume of orders, they are the best ones in terms of late deliveries;
      3
      * The worst months for deliveries are February, March and November. The first two are related to a very conturbated period for Brazil, every year: Carnaval and Easter holidays. The country becomes rather inneficient and chaotic, since within those 40 days there are only around 23 working days. November on the other hand is related to both holidays and people getting more money from their jobs - Brazil has what we call the 13th salary, when every employer is demanded to pay, as the name suggests, a 13th salary to all employees. Many companies opt to make those payments through the months of November and December.

      As expected, Brazil's highest GDP state (Sao Paulo) contains, by far, the biggest amount of orders, followed by Rio de Janeiro and Minas Gerais. Some interesting insights brought by the plot:
      2
      * Although SP has the biggest amount of orders, its delayed delivery percentage is not amongst the biggest ones;
      3
      * RR (Roraima) present a shocking 33% of delayed deliveries - knowledge of the country explains this very well, since RR is a very remote place, above the Amazon forest, so not many deliveries must be made there (3, when inspecting the database);
      4
      * AL is litterally the most isolated state of the country, with some deliveries, but not expressive;
      5
      * The first expressive state in terms of both late deliveries and amount of orders is Rio de Janeiro. This is very expected, since the state suffers from inneficiency, heavy traffic, many road accidents and poor public safety.

      As expected, Brazil's highest GDP state (Sao Paulo) contains, by far, the biggest amount of orders, followed by Rio de Janeiro and Minas Gerais. Some interesting insights brought by the plot:

      • The first expressive state in terms of both late deliveries and amount of orders is Rio de Janeiro. This is very expected, since the state suffers from inneficiency, heavy traffic, many road accidents and poor public safety.

      4) Conclusion¶

      The present study delivers two strategies to handle their respective KPIs:
      2
      ​
      3
      1. Credit card payment installments handling to improve the financial performance indicator of accounts receivable;
      4
      1. Reviews' natural language processing to improve the commercial performance indicator of customer satisfaction.
      5
      ​
      6
      The first one showed a 16% improvement in an indicator that is crucial for financial health of a company, especially when it comes to cashflow and providing warranty to banking institutions in relation to loans. The second one pinpointed exactly what could be pursued to tackle the majority (more than 67%) of bad reviews, thus shinning light into what can be done to improve customer satisfaction.
      7
      ​
      8
      Both deliveries carry great potential in the real world, providing operational and commercial improvements, respectively.

      The present study delivers two strategies to handle their respective KPIs:

      1. Credit card payment installments handling to improve the financial performance indicator of accounts receivable;
      2. Reviews' natural language processing to improve the commercial performance indicator of customer satisfaction.

      The first one showed a 16% improvement in an indicator that is crucial for financial health of a company, especially when it comes to cashflow and providing warranty to banking institutions in relation to loans. The second one pinpointed exactly what could be pursued to tackle the majority (more than 67%) of bad reviews, thus shinning light into what can be done to improve customer satisfaction.

      Both deliveries carry great potential in the real world, providing operational and commercial improvements, respectively.
